  "runtimeMin": 100,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Joanna Robinson fill out their ballots for all 23 categories at the 94th Academy Awards, days after Coda's PGA win turned Best Picture into a real two-horse race with The Power of the Dog. They split on the top prize (Robinson stays with Coda, Fennessy takes Power of the Dog) but agree Dune should win it, and call a Dune sweep of the below-the-line categories: sound, editing, production design, cinematography, score, and visual effects. They also split on Best Original Song, Best Documentary Short, and both screenplay categories. First, a rundown of what to expect from Sunday's truncated telecast.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Coda vs. The Power of the Dog",
      "note": "the PGA win and the state of the race",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "CODA",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Swept Sundance (Grand Jury Prize, Best Director, an acting prize, the Audience Award), then got a quiet August 2021 release before its Apple-funded campaign turned it into a genuine Best Picture threat. Its PGA win predicted seven of the last ten Best Picture winners; Robinson says she was 'on the Coda surge' before Bill Simmons was."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Power of the Dog",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "The presumed front-runner for months, and Netflix's latest shot at a Best Picture it's never won despite backing Roma, Marriage Story, and The Irishman. Both hosts think it's a genuinely strong film even as they debate whether Coda's late surge has overtaken it."
        }
      ]
